433. The spelling sequius is repeatedly found in the old writers in the place of the common forms secius or setius. The quantity of the e in se· is somewhat doubtful: Fleckeisen holds it to be short, on account of a line of Afranius (Ribb. Gom. rell. p. 170), where however the long e would do equally well: see Gorssen, krit. beitr. p. 7. Oorssen considers this line of the Aulularia to be an iambic septenarius: quid fecimus, quid diximus tibi sequius quam uelles? but this metre would be en- tirely out of place in the present scene.
